##Post 1 (2026)

A lesson I just learned the hard way: Sometimes a marketing partnership is not overpriced. It’s under-scoped.
What looks like "one sponsored post" on paper can slowly become multiple rounds of feedback disguised as "just one more question," messaging by committee, creative restrictions, and a timeline that keeps getting squeezed with every additional nit.
That doesn't always mean someone's doing something wrong. Sometimes it just means the process and the price no longer match.
I just had to walk away from one of those situations, and while I don't feel great about it, I don't have any regrets either.
If a sponsored deliverable requires multiple rounds of approval at the concept stage alone, it needs to be priced like a premium asset. At that point, the client isn't just paying for brand awareness or social media impressions; they're paying for the work itself. Anyway, lesson learned; rates adjusted.
And on that note: I'm open to creator marketing partnerships, especially ones that value strong ideas, clear process, and mutual respect. Send me a note if you think we might be a fit

##Post 2 (2026))

Best practices are the "beige" of marketing.
Not bad enough to fail. Not good enough for anyone to actually care.
Because best practices are just the average of tactics derived from data across many audiences and many contexts. And today, when everyone has access to the same AI tools, the same algorithm guides, and the same playbooks, average is increasingly invisible.
When you're marketing to the statistical average, you're basically marketing to no one.
What to do? Audience research. Learn the communities they hang out in, how they describe their problems, what they actually pay attention to. 
It's not about having the biggest budget or even being the most creative. It's about knowing your audience well enough to show up in the right places, say the right things, and make the right people feel like the content was made specifically for them.

